text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Expansion: Linguistic Discrimination by Examiners%0a:Author: BrandonW%0a:Original: [[Articles.DiscriminationInTestsAndLanguageLearningTools|DiscriminationInTestsAndLanguageLearningTools]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.rajeev_g|rajeev_g]]%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 08.05.2021 - 19:25%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-021003-208250#%0a* [-10.05.2021 - 19:10-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-021003-208250#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aExaminers have sometimes inaccurately assess children from linguistic backgrounds other than Standard American English. One result that has occurred is that minorities are overrepresented in special education programs. A reason that inaccurate assessments occur is that an examiner may not be fully familiar with a person's cultural/linguistic background. An example is that in African American English, the sentence "he walks to school" is actually said as "he walk to school" as the third person "-s" is deleted. An examiner may believe that this is evidence of language disorder when in reality it is a part of the person's dialect. Another reason is that tests are written in Standard American English instead of in a speaker's linguistic background, so scores on the test maybe lower than what they should be.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
