diff:1620527146:1620527146:=1,38d0%0a%3c :Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a%3c :Expansion: Linguistic Discrimination by Examiners%0a%3c :Author: BrandonW%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.DiscriminationInTestsAndLanguageLearningTools|DiscriminationInTestsAndLanguageLearningTools]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.rajeev_g|rajeev_g]]%0a%3c :Section: C%0a%3c :Completed: 08.05.2021 - 19:25%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Examiners have sometimes inaccurately assess children from linguistic backgrounds other than Standard American English. One result that has occurred is that minorities are overrepresented in special education programs. A reason that inaccurate assessments occur is that an examiner may not be fully familiar with a person's cultural/linguistic background. An example is that in African American English, the sentence "he walks to school" is actually said as "he walk to school" as the third person "-s" is deleted. An examiner may believe that this is evidence of language disorder when in reality it is a part of the person's dialect. Another reason is that tests are written in Standard American English instead of in a speaker's linguistic background, so scores on the test maybe lower than what they should be.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
